data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assert methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count check with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all items satisfy a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Should contain an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | `Assert.IsTrue(condition, "msg")` | Always add a message for boolean asserts |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and failure output |

**Other `CollectionAssert` helpers worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify collection contains a specific item
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// Verify all items are a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Verify no nulls
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// Verify two collections match (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Verify same items regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);
```

The general rule: prefer the **most specific assert** available — it gives you the best diagnostic output when tests fail.
